review: Definitely, definitely, definitely a new favorite book. Simultaneously broke my heart and then rebirthed it. A Tree Grows in Brooklyn is not even a boDefinitely, definitely, definitely a new favorite book. Simultaneously broke my heart and then rebirthed it. A Tree Grows in Brooklyn is not even a book — it’s a little piece of life you can hold in your hands. Yes, it’s about a distinct family in a distinct place at a distinct time but this little sliver somehow manages to express itself as everything that life is. The characters aren’t just characters but humans; the setting isn’t just a setting but a home. Every free moment I had for the past week or so became about being there with the Nolan’s in their corner of Brooklyn. In reading it you live a life and know the world — and I think those two things are what a book is meant to do more than anything else....more

author: Ishiguro, Kazuo*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Sometimes I wrestle with what to rate a book. NOT so with Never Let Me Go, which is funny, since at first, I thought the book started out slow, and itSometimes I wrestle with what to rate a book. NOT so with Never Let Me Go, which is funny, since at first, I thought the book started out slow, and it only grew on me as I read on. But now I think that just goes to show how brilliantly its secrets and science fiction elements are subtly weaved in. There is so much examined here—ethically, emotionally—so much that is raised and ripped, and really it’s useless for me to try to set it down because I will never describe it as profoundly as Never Let Me Go does. I will say, though, that the imprint of all of these ideas makes a book that is haunting and devastating, that had me not only crying but genuinely writhing on my couch at the fact that by the end, despite the name of the title, everything the characters have they must let go of. Kazuo Ishiguro strikes again as a master of tying anguish into simplicity, tension into the mundane, wisdom into quiet tragedy....more

review: Somewhere along the way of the world’s spinning and this story’s un-spinning, this book comes to inhabit the corners, the pathways of your mind until Somewhere along the way of the world’s spinning and this story’s un-spinning, this book comes to inhabit the corners, the pathways of your mind until it enters a deep, root place—what we recognize as the truth. The characters, the lives, the idea that we are all tied to one another in ways we are completely unaware of are so real, so undeniably, humanly real. With its relatively limited array of characters, Let the Great World Spin provides a reflection of the world entire and the forces that move us in and out of each other’s lives, that move us through our own lives. review: this book is a perfume in and of itself. it’s intoxicating—tantalizingly dark, wonderful, and absurd. and if part of what marks a great perfume is itsthis book is a perfume in and of itself. it’s intoxicating—tantalizingly dark, wonderful, and absurd. and if part of what marks a great perfume is its uniqueness, then “Perfume”, the novel, is one of the greatest perfumes of all time. seriously, i’ve never read a book like this one before. the story, and the one-and-only Grenouille, are so shockingly—sometimes even hilariously—strange, even while (and perhaps why) they remain stunningly crafted and magnificent. the idea of the power of aroma is a brilliant, sensuous one—and Suskind blends this masterfully with an element of the grotesque and vile—really just the root ugliness of human nature and the grip our senses have on us. AH, i could rave about this book forever. i know the scent of “Perfume” will linger in my head for a long time after. it’s just so marvelously disturbing. if by the end of the novel, Grenouille has become a master of scents, then by the end, Suskind has proved himself a master of pure storytelling too....more

review: what is beautiful about this story is that it meets the improbable gauntlet it throws down—it does make you believe in God—but not in the way one woulwhat is beautiful about this story is that it meets the improbable gauntlet it throws down—it does make you believe in God—but not in the way one would expect. no, it is not through miracles that Life of Pi makes one believe in God (though many play a role) or through unending talk about the nature of the divine or through anything of the sort. it is through the potent idea that Yann Martel crafts: reality as we take it in involves some level of imagination and interpretation; nothing is unequivocally “the truth.” so, given a choice between realities, why wouldn’t we choose the “better”—the more hopeful, colorful, moving—reality? the reality that involves something spiritual and deeper than what we can physically perceive, rather than a “yeastless” (to quote the book) world. i think this idea is genius. and i think this book is genius. the writing is whimsically brilliant—both witty and poignant and utterly unique. as a craft of literature, i think Life of Pi is a modern classic. and one more note—Richard Parker is SO adorable...more

review: i know that This Side of Paradise is far from the side of F. Scott Fitzgerald’s most well-crafted works—and yet, this book is unbelievably comforting i know that This Side of Paradise is far from the side of F. Scott Fitzgerald’s most well-crafted works—and yet, this book is unbelievably comforting to me for no rational reason; it just captures something so essential in restless, passionate, confusing youth. i see a reflection of myself in Amory and his discovering of himself. Fitzgerald’s writing is more beautiful than words can describe, as always. however, this book can lag at times, and Amory can be insufferable, and little is streamlined; ideas, though captivating, are strewn randomly here and there. it lacks the expertise of an experienced novelist. but still, i return to that capturing of some fundamental quality of how finding yourself in youth, in all its glory and suffering, simply feels. it transcends time period and experience. when Amory parts with Tom at Princeton for the war, the chapter ends with, “Oh, seep that never dreams, and dream that never tires, press from the petals of the lotus flower, something of this to keep, the essence of an hour.” i think everyone, when looking back on the expanse of their childhood, can sense the profundity of that statement....more

title: Alexander Hamilton
author: Chernow, Ron
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: i never expected to read an 832-page biography about a Founding Father—but i did, and i LOVED it!Ron Chernow’s biography is brilliant because it blendi never expected to read an 832-page biography about a Founding Father—but i did, and i LOVED it!Ron Chernow’s biography is brilliant because it blends an incredibly fascinating subject with an incredibly talented author. Chernow was able to paint a picture not only of the almost-improbable life of Alexander Hamilton but of the whole of 18th-century America. he covers much more than just Hamilton’s participation in certain affairs; he further explains what these things meant in early-American society and how they shaped the future of the country. but to me, the biggest genius of this book lies in the fact that Chernow gave such a story-telling flair to the life of Hamilton. he turned events that might otherwise be thought boring and made them as entertaining as the events of a novel. his portraits of the Founding Fathers are so in depth, and they are humanized in a way i have rarely seen before. Chernow takes these far-away, “God-like” men and turns them into real, true people with flaws and worries and passions. Chernow also definitely changed my opinion on some of the Founding Fathers (ahem… Thomas Jefferson…)however, with all this in mind, i would also warn that this book is definitely hefty; it took me two and a half months to finish it. everyone’s reading pace differs, but i think you should be prepared to expend a lot of time into the experience of this book—not because it’s dull and difficult to get through but because there is just such a depth of information and insight. however, if you are a fan of Alexander Hamilton and American history (like i am), i’m sure all of this information will be very interesting to you. all in all, i think this is a very powerful and moving book—just as inspirational as the Hamilton play—which taught me SO much about the founding of the United States and the people who played a role in it. any Hamilton fan, or really anyone interested in that time period, would thoroughly enjoy this book. and yes, i tried not to make Hamilton play references throughout this . it was hard. and to finish with this quote from the introduction of the book:“Today, we are indisputably the heirs to Hamilton’s America, and to repudiate his legacy is, in many ways, to repudiate the modern world.”...more
